<setup>
  <math name="g">y = 4-x</math>
  <math name="A">-1</math>
  <number name="B">2</number>
  <number name="C">4</number>
</setup>  

  <p>
    Consider the functions given by
    <m>f(x) = 5-(x-1)^2</m> and <m>g(x) = 4-x</m>.
  </p>

  <p> 
    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <p>
          State an equation whose solutions are the <m>x</m>-values
          where the graphs of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> intersect.
        </p>
        <p><answer>-x^2+3x=0</answer></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Solve your equation in (a) to find the <m>x</m>-values where the graphs of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> intersect.  If there is more than one such <m>x</m>-value, separate them with commas.
        </p>
        <p><answer><mathList unordered>0 3</mathList></answer></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use these <m>x</m>-values to find the points of intersection
          between the graphs of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>.  State each intersection point as an ordered pair; if there is more than one, separate them with commas.
        </p>
        <p><answer><mathList unordered>(0,4) (3,1)</mathList></answer></p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Drag the three points in the following figure to generate an accurate graph of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>.  Start by arranging the intersection points of the line and parabola in the correct locations, and then adjust the third point to accurately reflect the quadratic function <m>f</m>.
        </p>
        <graph size="medium" xmin="-6" xmax="6" ymin="-6" ymax="6" showNavigation="false" fixAxes="true">
          <point name="P1">
            (-3,1)
            <constraints>
              <attractToGrid/>
            </constraints>
          </point>
          <point name="P2">
            (5,3)
            <constraints>
              <attractToGrid/>
            </constraints>
          </point>
          <point name="P3">
            (1,0)
            <constraints>
              <attractTo><parabola through="(0,4) (1,5) (3,1)"/></attractTo>
            </constraints>
          </point>
          <line name="G" through="$P1 $P2" styleNumber="2"><label><m>g</m></label></line>
          <parabola name="F" through="$P1 $P2 $P3" styleNumber="3"><label><m>f</m></label></parabola>
        </graph>

  <answer name="correct" simplifyOnCompare> 
    <award>
      <when> $G.slope = -1 and $F.a = $A and $F.b = $B and $F.c = $C
      </when>
    </award>
  </answer>
 
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Find and evaluate exactly an integral expression that represents the area between
          <m>y = f(x)</m> and the <m>x</m>-axis on the interval between the intersection points of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>.  Once you identify the lower and upper limits of integration, those numbers will appear in the integral expression below.
        </p>
        <p>
          lower limit of integration: <m>a = </m> <answer name="a">0</answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          upper limit of integration: <m>b = </m> <answer name="b">3</answer>
        </p>

        <p>
          Integral expression for area between <m>y = f(x)</m> and the <m>x</m>-axis: 
        </p>
        <p>  
          <m>\displaystyle\int_{$a}^{$b}</m><mathInput name="int1" minWidth="100"/><m>dx \,</m><answer><award><when>$int1 = 5-(x-1)^2</when></award></answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          Numerical value of the area, <m>A_1</m>, between <m>y = f(x)</m> and the <m>x</m>-axis, on the interval between the intersection points of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>:
        </p>
        <p>   
          <m>A_1 = </m><answer>12</answer>
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Find and evaluate exactly an integral expression that represents the area between
          <m>y = g(x)</m> and the <m>x</m>-axis on the interval between the intersection points of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>.  Once you identify the lower and upper limits of integration, those numbers will appear in the integral expression below.
        </p>
        <p>
          lower limit of integration: <m>c = </m> <answer name="c">0</answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          upper limit of integration: <m>d = </m> <answer name="d">3</answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          Integral expression for area between <m>y = g(x)</m> and the <m>x</m>-axis: 
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle\int_{$c}^{$d}</m><mathInput name="int2" minWidth="100"/><m>dx \,</m><answer><award><when>$int2 = 4-x</when></award></answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          Numerical value of the area, <m>A_2</m>, between <m>y = g(x)</m> and the <m>x</m>-axis, on the interval between the intersection points of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>: 
        </p>
        <p>  
          <m>A_2 = </m> <answer>12-9/2</answer>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Complete the following sentences to explain how we now determine the value of the exact area between <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> on the interval between their intersection points.
        </p>  
        <p>
          Since both functions are positive on the interval between their intersection points, and on that interval <m>f(x)</m> is always <answer><choiceInput inline>
            <choice>?</choice>
            <choice>less than or equal to</choice>
            <choice>equal to</choice>
            <choice credit="1">greater than or equal to</choice>
          </choiceInput></answer> <m>g(x)</m>, once we have found the exact area <m>A_1</m> between <m>f</m> and the <m>x</m>-axis on the interval, and the exact area <m>A_2</m> between <m>g</m> and the <m>x</m>-axis on the interval, the exact area between <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> on the interval is
          <answer><choiceInput>
            <choice><m>A_1 + A_2</m></choice>
            <choice credit="1"><m>A_1 - A_2</m></choice>
            <choice><m>A_2 - A_1</m></choice>
          </choiceInput></answer>
          and thus the exact area <m>A</m> between <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> on the interval is 
        </p>  
        <p>
            <m>A = </m><answer>9/2</answer>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>